  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">WASH Assistance for Affected Populations in Syria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed project aims to improve health amp quality of life among conflict-affected, water stressed IDPs amp host communities in Aleppo, Daraa and Rural Damascus governorates. The targeted sub-districts within these governorates have been rated as suffering from severe amp critical problems as per the WASH sector analysis. From 30% to 80% of the communities in these targeted areas do not have direct access to water. In Rural Damascus, two of the three main water sources are out of use due to conflict and security constraints. Residents are forced to get water for personal consumption through water trucking. Oxfam&#x2019;s interventions have revealed that affected communities are spending as much as a third of their income on water. Similarly, in Aleppo, communities are forced to opt for water trucking, especially since the main power source for the city has been cut for over four months now. The situation has been further compounded in the city recently as ISIL has cut off water altogether from Khafse, which is the main source of water for Aleppo city and eastern rural Aleppo, rendering the population without even basic drinking water. In Daraa, the Al-Ashari pumping station also frequently damaged as a result of active conflict with residents forced to pay for water, with per cubic meter (1000 ltr) of water costing upwards of 500 Syrian Pounds against the cost pre conflict of 2.5 SYP. With regards to the lack of water, the affected population is also suffering from water borne amp water washed diseases, further compounded by food insecurity amp high levels of malnutrition. In light of these complex issues, Oxfam is proposing to undertake rehabilitation of targeted water systems in order to provide adequate, safe, durable water solutions for IDPs amp host communities in three governorates. Additionally, Oxfam will also be conducting awareness raising sessions on hygiene and water conservation, coupled with the distribution of hygiene and dignity items in collective shelters in Aleppo/ Rural Damascus depending upon humanitarian access.</narrative>
  </description>
